               <msContents>
                  <summary> This first book of the <title>Mas̲navī-i Ma‘navī</title> (Spiritual
                     Couplets) by Jalāl al-Dīn Rūmī (1207–1273) opens with a brief Arabic preface. A
                     scribe named <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" role="scr" key="person_f7822"
                        >Ḥamzah ibn Umah</persName> completed the volume in <date
                        calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1483" to="1484">842 AH (1438–39
                     CE)</date>.</summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_983-item1">
                     <author ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/98930150" key="person_98930150">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Jalāl al-Dīn Rūmī,
                           1207–1273</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">جلال الدین رومی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor role="com" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66900471" key="person_66900471">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Sulṭān Valad, 1226–1312</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName  xml:lang="fa">سلطان ولد</persName>
                     </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20506" change="#ids-cleanup"
                        >Mas̲navī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_20506" change="#ids-cleanup">مثنوی</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20506" change="#ids-cleanup"
                        >Mas̲navī-i Ma‘navī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_20506" change="#ids-cleanup"> مثنوی
                        معنوی</title>
                     <editor role="scr"><persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f7822">Ḥamzah
                           ibn Umah</persName><lb/> 
                        <persName key="person_f7822" xml:lang="fa">همزة ابن أمة</persName></editor>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmala"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> هذا كتاب المثنوي، وهو أصول أصول أصول الدين في كشف أسرار
                        الوصول واليقين وهو فقه الله الأكبر، و شرع الله الأزهر، وبرهان الله الأطهر
                        يشرق اشراقا آنور من الإصباح، مثل نوره كمشكاة فيها مصباح وهو جنان الجنان
                        والعيون و الأغصان وعند أصحاب المقامات والكرامات </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="103a" to="103a"> برگ ۱۰۳ر (Folio
                           103a):</locus> صبر کن و الله اعلم بالصواب. </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa"><locus from="103a" to="103a"> برگ ۱۰۳ر (Folio
                           103a):</locus> تمت بعون الملک التواب * الواسع العلی الکبیر الوهاب | علی
                        ید اضعف العباد حمزه بن امة * عفی عنهما الله ذو القعدة(؟) | و صلّی الله علی
                        سیدنا محمد واله وصحبه اجمعین * وغفر لسائن المؤمنان والمؤمنات آمین | سنه سته
                        و اربعین و ثمانمائه * من الخجرة النبی الامي ذی الفضل والمنة. </colophon>
                     <colophon>Completed by <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f7822"
                           >Ḥamzah Ibn Umah</persName> on <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1483"
                           to="1484">842 AH (1438–39 CE)</date>.</colophon>
                     <note>The preface on folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> and commencement
                        of the poem proper on folio <locus from="2a" to="2a">2a</locus> published by
                        Rafiee-Rad, plates 7–8. </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>For other copies of this work held in the Rylands, see <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6652"><idno>Persian
                           MS 17</idno></ref>, <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6691">21</ref>,
                        <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7223"
                           >72</ref>, <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6695"
                              >213</ref>, <ref
                                 target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6720">236</ref>,
                        <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6736"
                           >250–255</ref> (Books I–VI), <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7301">795</ref>,
                        <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7356"
                           >847</ref>, <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7357">848</ref>,
                        <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7438"
                           >926</ref>, and <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26584">984</ref>, the last being the earliest, completed in <date cert="high"
                                 calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1357-01-02">9 Muḥarram 758 AH (2 January
                                 1357 CE)</date>, about 85 years after the author first composed it. For critical editions, see Isti‘lāmī and
                        Furūzānfar. For a recent English translation of the first two books based on
                        the former edition, see Williams. For earlier translations, see Arberry,
                        Nicholson, and Whinfield.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
